    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-09-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-09-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="437"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d437">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">White</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United States Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-09-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 11, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. White, chargé d’affaires, refers to the Department’s instructions of the
                        29th,<note n="1" xml:id="d437fn1">Circular telegram, printed <ref
                            target="#pg_304">p. 304</ref>.</note> and reports that he is advised
                    that the British ambassador at St. Petersburg is instructed to acquaint the
                    Russian foreign office that Her Majesty’s Government have received
                    communications from their officers in the Far East in a somewhat imperfect form,
                    and, without forecasting the course which it will be expedient to pursue in the
                    future, they are of opinion that the time has not yet arrived when it will be
                    expedient to withdraw British forces from Pekin.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
